<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>

<chapter xml:id="ch11-popularity-contest" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Popularity Contest</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In the previous chapter we found that arrival times of tweets on a given topic seem to
      fit a Poisson distribution. Armed with that knowledge we can now develop a test to
      compare two different Twitter topics to see which one is more popular (or at least
      which one has a higher posting rate). We will use our knowledge of sampling
      distributions to understand the logic of the test.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-popularity-question">
    <title>Which Topic Is More Popular?</title>

    <p>
      Which topic on Twitter is more popular, Lady Gaga or Oprah Winfrey? This may not seem
      like an important question, but if we can make the comparison for these two topics, we
      can make it for any two topics. Certainly in the case of presidential elections, or a
      corruption scandal in the local news, or an international crisis, it could be a
      worthwhile goal to be able to analyze social media in a systematic way.
    </p>

    <p>
      Let's say we retrieved one hour's worth of Lady Gaga tweets and a similar amount of
      Oprah Winfrey tweets and just counted them up. What if it just happened to be a slow
      news day for Oprah? It really wouldn't be a fair comparison. A better approach would
      build upon what we learned in the previous chapter about how arrival times fit into the
      Poisson distribution. If the arrival curve is <q>steeper</q> for the first topic in
      contrast to the second topic, then the first topic is more active and therefore more
      popular.
    </p>

    <p>
      Using R's <c>rpois()</c> function we can illustrate these kinds of differences. The
      <c>rpois()</c> function will generate a stream of random numbers that roughly fit the
      Poisson distribution. The first argument is how many random numbers to generate and
      the second is the average delay between arrivals:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch11-rpois">
      <code>
rpois(10, 3)
mean(rpois(100, 3))
var(rpois(100, 3))
hist(rpois(1000, 3))
hist(rpois(1000, 10))
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      It is a curious fact of Poisson distributions that the mean and the variance of the
      ideal (theoretical) distribution are the same. In practice, for a small sample, they
      may be different.
    </p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-poisson-rate-comparison">
    <title>Comparing Two Poisson Rates</title>

    <p>
      Now that we understand how to visualize and compare Poisson distributions using
      simulated data, we can apply this to real Twitter data. We will use a helper function
      called <c>DelayProbability()</c> that takes a list of inter-arrival delay times and
      returns the cumulative probability of an arrival within each time interval. For each
      of the two topics we compare, we count the number of arrivals within the mean delay
      for the combined samples and pass those counts to R's built-in <c>poisson.test()</c>
      function:
    </p>

    <program language="r" xml:id="prog-ch11-poisson-test">
      <code>
poisson.test(c(333, 73), c(500, 500))
      </code>
    </program>

    <p>
      The output of <c>poisson.test()</c> provides several useful pieces of information.
      The most important is the 95% confidence interval around the observed rate ratio.
      The values of 3.53 and 5.96 represent the upper and lower limits of the 95%
      confidence interval around the observed rate ratio of 4.56. So we can be pretty sure
      (95% confidence) that Lady Gaga gets tweets at least 3.5 times as fast as Oprah.
      Because the confidence interval does not include 1 (which would mean the two rates
      are identical), we can be pretty certain that the observed rate ratio of 4.56 is not
      a statistical fluke.
    </p>

    <p>
      We can also use a bar chart to visualize the two Poisson cumulative probability
      curves side by side. The <c>gplots</c> package provides a <c>barplot2()</c> function
      that is useful for this purpose. When the two curves are very different (as in the
      Gaga vs. Oprah case) the difference is visually obvious. When they are similar
      (as in the Obama vs. Romney comparison) we need to rely on the confidence interval
      to know whether the difference is statistically reliable.
    </p>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch11">
    <title>Chapter Challenge</title>
    <exercise xml:id="ex-ch11-challenge">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write a function that takes two search strings as arguments and that returns
          the results of a Poisson rate ratio test on the arrival rates of tweets on the
          two topics. Your function should first run the necessary Twitter searches, then
          sort the tweets by ascending time of arrival and calculate the two vectors of
          time differentials. Use the mean of one of these vectors as the basis for
          comparison and for each vector, count how many events are at or below the mean.
          Use this information and the numbers of tweets requested to run the
          <c>poisson.test()</c> rate comparison.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>

